description: Just after I entered the woods, in a sunny clearing with several hackberry trees, I saw the first two Hackberry Emperors of the day, which was quite exciting. They were doing the emperor thing -- chasing after each other in the mid canopy and landing and posing on the hackberry limbs and leaves. I would go on to tally 26 individuals in the park. There is only one (!) previous iNaturalist record from Manhattan -- clearly Inwood Hill Park is dramatically under-surveyed.

description: I was ecstatic to find this hairstreak, the first of a dozen today. When I first saw it, it was in aerial battle with a rival, but then it settled on a poison ivy leaf to pose. This species had been reported from Inwood Hill Park in the 1990s, but there have been no reports in the last decade on iNaturalist, NABA, or BAMONA, so I didn't know whether the species persists in the park -- clearly it does, and what a gorgeous jewel of a butterfly.

description: Egg shaped leaves with entire margins and pointed tips.  The branches get very bushy and messy looking.  Sharp 1/2 inch thorns can be found on the branches.   The bark is flaky and orange underneath.  Orange at the base of the trunk.  Several large fruit can be seen high up in the canopy.  The broken petiole exudes a white latex, similar to White mulberry, as do the torn leaves.  The bark is also quite similar to that of Morus alba.  In fact, it’s so similar that I mistook a large White mulberry not far from here for an Osage orange.  It’s no coincidence that the Osage orange is so similar to the White mulberry, they are both in the Moraceae family.  This tree was growing right next to a large White mulberry.

description:
From https://www.eattheweeds.com/tag/canadian-honewort/

The Canadian Honewort, Cryptotaenia canadensis, grows all the way down to Florida, and covers the eastern two third of North America. A member of the carrot family, it can be found growing along streams and creeks or in low, wet ground. The entire plant is edible, cooked, root to flowers. Flowering season is May to August and the blossom are small. Also called Wild Chervil, the roots are usually boiled in salted water and served with oil, young leaves and stems are soaked in water to moderate flavor then cooked as a pot herb. Cooked flowers are edible as well.  You can add a small portion to salads for their aromatic quality. Seeds are used for flavoring and the stems candied. Cryptotaenia japonica can be used in a similar way but needs far less cooking, usually just blanching. In warmer areas don’t mistake Tripogandra multiflora for it. The latter has black stems
